.TH "NC" "1" "2026\-04\-16" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nc \- cross\-platform netcat replacement for TCP/UDP send/receive, port
checks, and TLS clients
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]nc\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]host\f[R] \f[I]port\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]nc\f[R] \f[B]\(enlisten\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]port\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]nc\f[R] \f[B]\(encheck\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]host\f[R]
\f[I]port\-spec\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]nc\f[R] opens a TCP or UDP connection, listens for one inbound
connection, or probes one or more ports for openness.
Familiar \f[B]nc\f[R] short flags (\f[B]\-z\f[R], \f[B]\-l\f[R],
\f[B]\-u\f[R], \f[B]\-w\f[R], \f[B]\-4\f[R], \f[B]\-6\f[R]) are accepted
alongside descriptive long\-form flags.
.PP
Connect mode (default) reads \f[I]stdin\f[R], sends it to the remote,
and writes the response to \f[I]stdout\f[R].
On stdin EOF, the write half of the socket is closed so request/response
protocols like HTTP do not hang.
Listen mode behaves the same way once a connection is accepted, but
exits after that single connection.
.PP
Check mode (\f[B]\-z\f[R] / \f[B]\(encheck\f[R]) opens a TCP connection
to each specified port, then closes it.
Open ports are printed one per line to \f[I]stdout\f[R].
Closed and timed\-out ports go to \f[I]stderr\f[R] only under
\f[B]\(enverbose\f[R].
The exit code reflects the worst result seen across all probed ports.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\(enlisten\f[R], \f[B]\-l\f[R]
Listen for one inbound connection (TCP) or one datagram (UDP).
Exits after the single exchange.
.TP
\f[B]\(encheck\f[R], \f[B]\-z\f[R]
Probe port(s) and exit without exchanging data.
.TP
\f[B]\(enudp\f[R], \f[B]\-u\f[R]
Use UDP.
Default is TCP.
.TP
\f[B]\(entls\f[R], \f[B]\(enssl\f[R]
Wrap the TCP connection in TLS.
Client mode only; server\-side TLS is not supported.
.TP
\f[B]\(eninsecure\f[R]
Skip TLS certificate validation.
A warning is printed to stderr.
Useful for self\-signed development servers.
.TP
\f[B]\(enipv4\f[R], \f[B]\-4\f[R]
Force IPv4 address resolution.
.TP
\f[B]\(enipv6\f[R], \f[B]\-6\f[R]
Force IPv6 address resolution.
.TP
\f[B]\(entimeout\f[R] \f[I]SEC\f[R], \f[B]\-w\f[R] \f[I]SEC\f[R]
Connect and idle timeout in seconds (1\-3600).
Default is 10 seconds in check mode; unlimited elsewhere.
.TP
\f[B]\(enbind\f[R] \f[I]ADDR\f[R]
Listener bind address.
Default is all interfaces.
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-shutdown\f[R]
Do not half\-close the socket on stdin EOF.
Only needed for protocols that treat half\-close as a full disconnect.
.TP
\f[B]\(enverbose\f[R], \f[B]\-v\f[R]
In check mode, also print closed/timeout ports to stderr.
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Emit a JSON summary to stderr after the run.
.TP
\f[B]\(endescribe\f[R]
Output structured tool metadata as JSON (flags, examples, composability)
and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R]
Force coloured output, overriding \f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable coloured output.
.TP
\f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Show help and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version and exit.
.SH PORT SPECIFIERS
Check mode accepts single ports, ranges, lists, or a combination:
.IP
.EX
nc \-z host 80                       # single
nc \-z host 80\-1000                  # range (inclusive)
nc \-z host 80,443,8080              # list
nc \-z host 80\-100,443,8080\-8090     # mixed
.EE
.PP
All ports must be 1\-65535.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success \(em connection completed, all probed ports open, or listener
served one exchange.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Connection refused, DNS failure, host unreachable, bind failure, any
closed port in check mode, or TLS handshake failure.
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
Timeout during connect or port check.
.TP
\f[B]125\f[R]
Usage error (bad arguments).
.TP
\f[B]126\f[R]
Permission denied (e.g.\ bind to privileged port without elevation).
.TP
\f[B]130\f[R]
Interrupted (Ctrl\-C).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set, disables coloured output (no\-color.org).
.SH HALF\-CLOSE BEHAVIOUR
When stdin reaches EOF in connect or listen mode, \f[B]nc\f[R] calls
\f[B]Socket.Shutdown(Send)\f[R] so the peer sees end\-of\-stream on its
read side.
Without this, request/response protocols like HTTP hang \(em the peer
waits for more request bytes before responding.
Use \f[B]\(enno\-shutdown\f[R] only for the rare protocols that treat
half\-close as a full disconnect.
.SH OUTPUT STREAMS
.TP
\f[B]stdout\f[R]
Bytes received from the remote (connect/listen modes) or one line per
open port (check mode).
.TP
\f[B]stderr\f[R]
Status messages, errors, warnings, and the \f[B]\(enjson\f[R] summary
when enabled.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
nc \-z target.com 443

nc \-z target.com 80,443,5432 \-\-json

echo \(dqGET / HTTP/1.0\(dq | nc target.com 80

nc \-\-tls api.example.com 443

nc \-u dnsserver 53 < query.bin

nc \-l 8080

nc target.com 80 < request.bin > response.bin

nc \-\-describe
.EE
